\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Plant species:}
    \begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
      \item \textit{Arabidopsis thaliana} (C$_3$): a drought-sensitive eudicot.
      \item \textit{Kalanchoe fedtschenkoi} (CAM): an obligate Crassulacean Acid Metabolism species, moderately drought-tolerant.
    \end{enumerate}

  \item \textbf{Herbivore:} A laboratory population of \textit{Plutella xylostella} (diamondback moth) engineered at a single Mendelian locus (\textit{P}), with two alleles:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item \textit{P}$_\mathrm{A}$: confers larval feeding preference and increased fitness on C$_3$ hosts only.
      \item \textit{P}$_\mathrm{K}$: confers larval feeding preference and increased fitness on CAM hosts only.
    \end{itemize}
    The heterozygote (\textit{P}$_\mathrm{A}$\textit{P}$_\mathrm{K}$) exhibits intermediate, generalized feeding, but cannot outperform the more abundant specialist host genotype (no overdominance: fitness is always between the two homozygotes).

  \item \textbf{Setup:} The plants are established from seed and allowed to fill the available area equally under well-watered conditions: \( A^A_\mathrm{leaf,0} = A^K_\mathrm{leaf,0} = 0.50\,\text{m}^2 \). Leaves are the only aboveground biomass; all dead tissue is removed when lost. Both species have identical leaf mass per unit area (LMA = 50.0\,g\,m$^{-2}$).
\end{itemize}

After 8 weeks, a simulated drought is imposed and maintained by reducing daily water input to \textbf{10\% of plant daily transpiration needs}. This causes:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textit{Instantaneous} 50.0\% \textbf{reduction in leaf area and biomass} for A. thaliana (i.e. live \( A^A_\mathrm{leaf,1} = 0.25\,\mathrm{m}^2 \)), with all lost tissue physically removed.
  \item \textbf{Gradual, 10.0\% reduction} in leaf area and biomass for K. fedtschenkoi (i.e. steady-state \( A^K_\mathrm{leaf,1} = 0.45\,\mathrm{m}^2 \)), accounting for mild CAM vulnerability.
\end{itemize}
The system stabilizes at these post-stress biomasses for \textbf{all subsequent generations}.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Plant species & Equilibrium leaf area ($A^X_\mathrm{leaf,1}$, $\text{m}^2$) & Equilibrium leaf biomass ($B_X$, $\text{g}$) \\
\midrule
\textit{A. thaliana} & 0.25 & $B_A = 0.25~\times~50.0 = 12.5$ \\
\textit{K. fedtschenkoi} & 0.45 & $B_K = 0.45~\times~50.0 = 22.5$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\noindent\textbf{Herbivore fitness functions (per genotype):}
The population breeds panmictically with non-overlapping generations of infinite size (neglecting drift), and viability selection on larvae only. Fitness is determined as a function of \textbf{current standing host leaf biomass}:
\begin{align*}
W_{AA}\ (\text{specialist on C}_3) &= 1 + s_S\, B_{A} \\
W_{KK}\ (\text{specialist on CAM})  &= 1 + s_S\, B_{K} \\
W_{AK}\ (\text{generalist})         &= 1 + s_G\,\frac{B_{A} + B_{K}}{2}
\end{align*}
where $s_S = 8.00 \times 10^{-3}\,\mathrm{g}^{-1}$ and $s_G = 6.00 \times 10^{-3}\,\mathrm{g}^{-1}$ (unit: $\mathrm{g}^{-1}$).

\textbf{Assumptions:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Herbivore fitness is solely a function of host biomass (via larval survival and development rate), with all rates deterministic.
  \item No gene-environment feedback: herbivores do not alter plant standing leaf biomass at equilibrium.
  \item All allele fitness effects are additive or intermediate (no overdominance or underdominance).
  \item Hardy–Weinberg frequencies apply each generation; population is infinite.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Task:}
Using only the data above, \textbf{calculate the equilibrium frequency of the $\mathbf{P_A}$ allele ($p_{\mathrm{eq}}$)} in the moth population under viability selection. Provide your answer to three decimal places.

\noindent \textbf{Table 1: Plant biomasses and fitness coefficients}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Genotype & Fitness formula                                                     & Value $W$ \\
\midrule
$\mathtt{P_A P_A}$ & $1 + s_S\,B_A$                               & $1 + 8.00 \times 10^{-3} \times 12.5$ \\
$\mathtt{P_K P_K}$ & $1 + s_S\,B_K$                               & $1 + 8.00 \times 10^{-3} \times 22.5$ \\
$\mathtt{P_A P_K}$ & $1 + s_G\,\big(\tfrac{B_A+B_K}{2}\big)$     & $1 + 6.00 \times 10^{-3} \times 17.5$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}",
